@misc{potter_brandt_nodate,
	title = {Brandt {Commission}},
	abstract = {The Brandt Commission, properly known as the Independent Commission on International Development Issues (ICIDI), was established in 1977 with the express aim of examining the world’s development needs in the 1980s and beyond. The Commission was chaired by Willy Brandt, the former Chancellor of the Federal Republic of Germany, and there were a total of eighteen commissioners, mainly consisting of former politicians and diplomats. Including the opening session, which took place in December 1977, the Commission met formally on ten occasions between 1977 and 1979. The recommendations of the Brandt Commission were outlined in its two published reports North–South: A Programme for Survival (1980) and Common Crisis: North–South Cooperation for World Recovery (1983). Having overviewed the origins and establishment of the Brandt Commission, details of the membership of the Commission and its schedule of meetings are reviewed, followed by its principal recommendations, employing the chapter headings used in the North–South report. In conclusion, a critical evaluation of the work of the Brandt Commission is presented. While the Commission is still seen as visionary by some, for its critics its recommendations were always idealistic, naı̈ve, and unrealistic.},
