@article{fabinyi_social-ecological_2014,
	title = {Social-ecological systems, social diversity, and power: insights from anthropology and political ecology},
	volume = {19},
	issn = {1708-3087},
	shorttitle = {Social-ecological systems, social diversity, and power},
	url = {http://www.ecologyandsociety.org/vol19/iss4/art28/},
	doi = {10.5751/ES-07029-190428},
	abstract = {A social-ecological system (SES) framework increasingly underpins the “resilience paradigm.” As with all models, the SES comes with particular biases. We explore these key biases. We critically examine how the SES resilience literature has attempted to define and analyze the social arena. We argue that much SES literature defines people’s interests and livelihoods as concerned primarily with the environment, and thereby underplays the role of other motivations and social institutions. We also highlight the SES resilience literature’s focus on institutions and organized social units, which misses key aspects of social diversity and power. Our key premise is the importance of inter- and multi-disciplinary perspectives. To illustrate this, we draw attention to the critique of earlier ecological anthropology that remains relevant for current conceptualizations of SESs, focusing on the concepts of social diversity and power. And we discuss insights from social anthropology and political ecology that have responded to this critique to develop different ways of incorporating social diversity and power into human-environment relations. Finally, we discuss how these social science perspectives can help improve the understanding of the “social” in SES resilience research.},
	language = {en},
	number = {4},
	urldate = {2019-03-01},
	journal = {Ecology and Society},
	author = {Fabinyi, Michael and Evans, Louisa and Foale, Simon J.},
	year = {2014},
	keywords = {SES, Power},
	annote = {Note: This is the synthesis paper for a special feature on exploring social-ecological resilience through the lends of the social sciences in Ecology and Society 19(4):28. 
This paper is at times brilliant and at other times gets in the muck by not defining terms like “power” up front. The sense that I get while reading the paper is that power is “something bad or sinister” operating in SES or between actors in an SES.
That said, there are a number of very useful insights in the paper that are very valuable. In addition, the citations in the paper are extensive and serve as a useful review of both SES key literature and extensive citations around power that are tangential to the field.
First, the paper argues that the social side of SES is under-theorized in a lot of the SES research:
“We argue that much of SES literature defines people’s interests and livelihoods as concerned primarily with the environment, and thereby underplays the role of other motivations and social institutions.”
Also the SES focus on “institutions and organized social units” misses key elements of inter-group power conflict and social diversity. [Here I am not totally sure what they mean by institutions with regard to this point and its one of the areas where the paper could use greater conceptual clarity].
The paper says that a lot of the SES lit tends to define “people’s interests and livelihoods are concerned primarily with the environment”, which they argue is insufficient for understanding the complexity of the social side of SES. One interesting take on this, is that if people’s interest were instead defined with respect to the entire productive base and their access to it, it might be a slightly more robust way of still modeling a human agent as a relatively rational actor, but with an expanded scope of concerns and resources with which to accumulate power.
Three main critiques in short:

“tendency to assume that within an SES, people’s knowledge, values, and livelihoods are concerned primarily with the environment"
“the tendency to aggregate or homogenize social complexity and thereby assume that people’s interests, expectations, and experiences are the same"
“value laden uses of resilience” where most people assume that resilience is a good thing, where in reality a system that includes great poverty and inequality can also be resilient.

Second the paper looks at this history of how two other fields (social anthropology and political ecology) integrated ideas of power in response to criticism that issues of power and agency were insufficiently integrated into their disciplines:
Social anthropology for example has only more recently begun to look at trade-offs in response to their greater awareness of diverse and contested interests at the community level. This led to an “increasing recognition in the environmental and academic and policy community that “win-win” outcomes are in many cases impossible to achieve, and so the goal of much governance should be how to address and negotiate between competing goals and perspectives of different stakeholders.”
The SES literature is only beginning to incorporate trade-offs (e.g. Robards et al 2011).
Another important change was the retheorization of the concept of community in social anthropology, which focused more on the history and special scales of community. This led to greater focus on linkages across scales and social diversity within the community itself.
Conclusion: The interdisciplinary “dialogue” over the issue of power may be of value to resilience studies in two ways: First by demonstrating the importance of recognizing and dealing with trade-offs and second through a more critical understanding how power operates. At the same time the authors caution against any grand frameworks of theories of everything in incorporating something as complex as power into SES (it’s too bad they did not even attempt a definition though…).
Tradeoffs: “By increasing the focus on social diversity within an SES, resilience studies would be better able to understand how current or changed system configuration affect different people in different ways.”
Power: “Importantly, power is not just focused on the material dimension but the discursive as well. A better understanding of the discursive dimensions of power in SESs would encourage resilience scientists to deconstruct whose voices become privileged and whose voices are silenced and why in debates over resilient SESs.” [This point engages both with a multiple faces/types of power point; but also with more STS/Foucault arguments of the role of power in shaping the very questions that get asked or the way problems are defined].
The authors recommend 4 ways to better include tradeoffs and power:

Greater reflection on how research questions are framed to focus on different points of view, conflict, contestation and micro-power dynamics. For example “situating resilience problem formulations in contestations over knowledge brings to the fore questions about whose resilience we are concerned with, and to what end.”
Incorporating frameworks from other disciplines. Presumably they mean frameworks for studying power and tradeoffs though somehow they failed to mention such a framework despite a list of other disciplines resilience studies is currently engaged with.
“Methodologically utilizing approaches that allow people to reflect on ‘the meaning of things’”. Especially using ethnographic and other qualitative research. I read this as a call for greater reflexivity in the research process.
“Consciously steering away from the normative bias often associated with resilience thinking”

 
Relevance to Project: It's a strong citation that the way SES deals with power is not quite robust enough and hence larger frameworks in sustainability science are unlikely to have dealt sufficiently with this issue either. It also clearly articulates the ways in which SES fails to deal with these issues. 

 
},
	file = {Fabinyi et al. - 2014 - Social-ecological systems, social diversity, and p.pdf:/Users/wyatthurt/Zotero/storage/9CS5SNAM/Fabinyi et al. - 2014 - Social-ecological systems, social diversity, and p.pdf:application/pdf}
}

