	abstract = {Taking the pulse of an ecosystem is not quite as straightforward as taking the pulse of a person, especially when that ecosystem is the Chesapeake Bay. At 195 miles long and 3,237 square miles in area, the size and complexity of the bay’s coupled social and ecological systems has challenged efforts to assess its health. Building on more than 30 y of research, Lefcheck et al. (1) offer an innovative way to take the pulse of this much loved and debilitated coastal estuary. By developing a model of the bay ecosystem that brings data from long-term, large-scale monitoring together with knowledge of the mechanisms underlying those patterns, Lefcheck et al. make a compelling case that ecosystem restoration initiatives of the last 30+ y are paying off.

