	annote = {
Ferguson critiques development projects taken on by first world nations. Ferguson argues that political powers look to increase their influence in other countries with low economic resources by promising aid through development. The author provides an in-depth case study of the Thaba-Tseka Development Project in Lesotho (1975–1984) to elucidate their point. Though this example he describes how development agencies have started and failed to implement desired changes although the side effects of these attempts have benefitted locals.
He analyzes the institutional framework within which development projects are organized and the surrounding "development discourse.” Despite the expertise and attention in formulating development projects, development agencies are often ignorant of the historical and political realities of the locals they intend to help. Development strategies need to be adopted and implemented with specific regions in mind. Development agencies have given false impressions of local economic circumstances to arouse support for further development. This, however, district the reality of locals and as a result development projects fail to achieve their objectives. He demonstrates this by examine specific cases from the 1975 World Report which shed light on local realties vs. constructed development-focused realities. Moreover, for the Lesotho case he explains that it was considered untouched by modern economic development but had rapid population growth. Yet many locals dis not perceive that they have been isolated from the world economy. In the same vein, when it comes to environmental management often western organizations are not familiar with the environment and how the local’s community engages with it, so they are not able to effectively assist locals. 
Ferguson shows how a misguided development approach in Lesotho actually acted as "anti-politics machine." It strengthened state presence in the region, extending the bureaucracy. In efforts to arouse support for development, the state had been represented as a benevolent actor which sought to empower its people. In fact, it various government ministries refused to cooperate and used project resources to further entrench the ruling party. Thus, while development is generally assumed to be positive, creating opportunities for locals through implemented projects in impoverished regions, these projects have unintended political consequences when they fail. They expand the power of the bureaucratic state and translate the political realities of poverty and powerlessness into technical problems, meant to be solved by development experts. He concludes that this bureaucracy could not have been instituted without the influence of political development projects. 
Relevance to paper: Focuses on how development mediated political outcomes, how global inequality affects local power structures, and how local communities are not empowered through development. Within the three-dimensional approach it fits most with Bachrach approach. Development projects strengthen political institutions, taking power away from those which development projects should seek to empower.
}
}

