	abstract = {Shaping policy for environmental sustainability depends upon decision-makers conceptualizing problems in ways that are either shared or similar enough to communicate about, diagnose, and act. The quality of this shared mental model of a social–ecological system (SES) is paramount to its effectiveness. Fundamentally, the mental model must integrate multiple kinds of knowledge about the system. If the decision-making body's assumptions about, description of, and solution for a problem do not to reflect the many ways stakeholders know a system, then the products of that decision-making process are viewed as illegitimate. Sustainability policy must fit the often subtle social order of the communities expected to implement it. In this essay, we discuss how a systems-based perspective can be a versatile tool for tackling these challenges of knowledge integration and decision-making in the context of a complex SES. Using social theory of Pierre Bourdieu, we construct a conceptual model that illustrates a route for integrating locally known social complexities (power, influence) gleaned from stakeholder interviews (N = 57). Stakeholders and end-user groups may dismiss any model that they perceive fails to satisfactorily account for specific, locally salient social nuances. Our approach leverages the overlapping notion of “capital” in social and ecological theory to demonstrate how reciprocal interactions between human and ecological systems can be adopted into tools for reaching viable solutions to SES problems. Keywords: Sustainability science, Social capital, Power, Boundary object, Water resources management, Floodplain development, Riparian ecology},
	language = {en},
	number = {2},
	urldate = {2019-03-19},
	journal = {European Journal of Sustainable Development},
	author = {Hall, Damon M. and Swannack, Todd M. and Lazarus, Eli D. and Peterson, Markus J. and Gilbertz, Susan J. and Horton, Cristi C. and Peterson, Tarla Rai},
	year = {2015},
	keywords = {Power},
	pages = {61--76--76},
	annote = {This paper looks at the importance of integrating local knowledge into policy solutions. If local stakeholders do not believe that the models and assumptions used in decision making processes accurately reflect the nuances of power and influence at the local level, they will view the products of the decision-making process as illegitimate.
They argue that boundary objects are one way to create the necessary transdisciplinary knowledge and mental models for better decision-making processes. They highlight the role of models as boundary objects and “the process of creating a model forces the model builders to enunciate clearly their held assumptions”. To illustrate this, they build an agent-based model of riparian decision making using both ecological and social capital (power) inputs into the model.
(The authors note that SES models tend to gloss over or oversimplify the social and political as opposed to the environmental systems probably due to the fact that the dynamics of social and political processes are more difficult to render in the abstract).
In order to construct a measure of social capital, the authors rely on the work of Pierre Bourdieu (1985-1993) on capital accumulation as an enabler of participants to influence social systems. “In formal terms, capital is the human capacity to act upon a system based on relative positions in the social and ecological logics of a situation.” Boudieu represents the social world as a world of “self-producing field of hierarchies where agents compete for symbolic and material resources”. He makes a very Gaventa-esqu point that power structures and the self-reinforcing accumulation of power is so embedded that agents often fail to recognize the underlying power structures.
To come up with a measurement of social capital, they break it down into economic capital, affiliative capital and cultural capital. The sum of these three types of capital belonging to the different agents in their model equals their total social capital allowing them to influence decisions in the agent based model.
The strange thing about the paper is that while they go to great lengths to set up the model, unless I am missing something they don't say much about what happens when they ran the model. Who wins, who loses, were there unexpected outcomes under different conditions. Did the model turn out to be a useful boundary object in the field setting? What did they learn from this?
Relevance to our project
The idea of capital accumulation and its link to ability to influence social systems is worth thinking about. This could be both manufactured capital, but also other forms of capital such as social capital. The authors do a very good job offering ways to think mathematically about the accumulation of capital that is not as easy to count as acres of land or number of automobiles.
It is a good idea to go back and read some from Bourdieu to think about the link between accumulation of capital over time and power. Can an accumulation of social capital in too few hands (too unequal) be as nefarious to SD outcomes as the accumulation of natural capital in too few hands? I think Gaventa’s book on Apalachia coal mining would say yes. The coal mining company was able if not to literally have more social capital, to design the institutions so they benefited their interests rather than the miners’ interests. Can one say this is to “have more” social capital?
I think the way they juxtapose social and ecological capital here is not quite right. The “natural” capital shows up in the model in two ways. The first is who has ownership of natural capital which in the end is part of their economic capital which influences their total “social capital”. The second way natural capital shows up is in the SES as in the frequency and severity of floods in the riverbank and how this is changed by the decisions of agents. In my opinion, this is not really a kind of capital but a property of the SES.},
	file = {Full Text PDF:/Users/wyatthurt/Zotero/storage/A34YPI4N/Hall et al. - 2015 - Integrating Social Power and Political Influence i.pdf:application/pdf;Snapshot:/Users/wyatthurt/Zotero/storage/ICJY6H88/237.html:text/html}
}

