	title = {The {Continuity} {Bias}: {A} {Failure} of {Imagination} in {Global} {Scenario} {SRtudies} and {Its} {Implications}},
	abstract = {Current social, political, economic, and environmental trends portend a period of profound changes. These may be by design or by default. In either case, the possibility of these changes deserves serious consideration in our scientific, political, and public discourses about the future. Thus, it is deeply disturbing that global scenario studies continue to discount plausible pathways that exhibit significant change, particularly those involving surprises and shocks that disturb otherwise smooth paths from the present. This gap represents a form of methodological stasis in scenario development, in spite of past calls to explicitly explore surprise events and discontinuities. It reflects a bias towards a gradualist theory of change, scientific reticence, and the lure of quantitative tractability. These are further exacerbated by the prevailing practices of scenario development and the fact that these studies are often embedded in decision and policymaking processes. The consequences are specious science, imprudent policymaking, and circumscribed public discourse. Ultimately, it represents a failure of the scientific imagination and leaves decision-makers and the general public less prepared for the risks and opportunities we will encounter as we navigate the coming years.},
