	annote = {BC comments on AGH comments:
 

From: Alicia Harley {\textless}agharley@gmail.com{\textgreater} on behalf of Alicia G. Harley {\textless}Alicia\_Harley@hks.harvard.edu{\textgreater}Sent: Tuesday, September 17, 2019 17:39To: Clark, William C. {\textless}william\_clark@hks.harvard.edu{\textgreater}Subject: Re: how deep is incumbency? (entrenched power in science, technology and innovation )
 




Hi Bill;
 
I read through the Stirling paper "How deep is incumbency?” With  a fine-tooth comb which took a while because its very dense. Here is my review which is also in Zotero. While its very dense, its well worth the effort as Stirling addresses many of the “what is the system” questions we have been struggling with and it may serve us well to adopt some of his language. 











BC: I started my comments on your comments below with your purple questions.   Maybe read those first, then come back up here for my secondary comments on your numbered points.  Also note that I have highlighted what seemed important to me with yellow in the text.











 
1. Stirling wants to expand the notion of incumbency from discipline specific like socio-technical incumbency to include any “domain of what might potentially be self to be salient to change in any given feature of the world, extends in principle to the totality of what exists or is variously imaginable around the world.” In other words, he is developing an approach that is balanced across multiple dimensions and perspectives on power and incumbency. “Without unduly redirecting scope for important nuances, disparities and context-specificities in particular settings [action situations].”  











